I would like to advocate Euclid classification.

It's either the case that time is one-dimensional or that time is multi-dimensional. If time is one-dimensional, then SCP-196 cannot die before he returns to 196X, because the past cannot be changed. If time is multi-dimensional, then the SCP-196 in captivity can die, because the SCP-196 that died in 196X is not the very same SCP-196 in captivity (they are from alternate timelines). While they may hardly know the actual nature of time (whether it is one- or multi-dimensional), Foundation scientists—with regularly above-average cleverness—must recognize that it is one or the other, and since a paradox cannot arise in either case, they would conclude that there is no reason to designate SCP-196 as Keter. In fact, there is nothing intrinsically anomalous about SCP-196 (unless he can time-travel of his own will); nevertheless, I can imagine the Foundation's wanting to retain SCP-196 because he is a known time-traveler: the Foundation may hope to bear witness to SCP-196's actual time-traveling and to learn more about their possibly harnessing such technology or abilities. So, they would designate SCP-196 as Euclid to uphold a standard of security.







